  <section class="section" id="t-overview">
    <div class="section-tag">🟪 terraform · 01</div>
    <h2>Overview &amp; Core Concepts</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">What Terraform actually does, why teams use it over clicking around the AWS console, and the core idea everything else builds on.</p>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">01</span> What is Terraform — and why not just use the AWS Console / CLI scripts?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> Clicking through the AWS Console to create infrastructure is like building furniture from memory every time — no instructions, easy to forget a step, impossible to repeat exactly. Terraform is the IKEA instruction manual — write down exactly what you want once, and run it any number of times to get the identical result.</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Infrastructure as Code (IaC):</strong> you describe the desired infrastructure in text files (HCL), and Terraform figures out the steps to make reality match that description.</li>
          <li><strong>Declarative, not imperative:</strong> you say "I want 3 EC2 instances and a security group" — not "run this command, then this one, then this one." Terraform diffs current vs desired state and only changes what's needed.</li>
          <li><strong>Provider-agnostic:</strong> the same workflow (<code>init</code>, <code>plan</code>, <code>apply</code>) works for AWS, Azure, GCP, Kubernetes, GitHub, Datadog — anything with a Terraform provider.</li>
          <li><strong>Why teams love it:</strong> infrastructure changes go through the same review process as code — a pull request, a diff, an approval — instead of someone quietly clicking a button in the console at 11pm.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">02</span> The core workflow — init, plan, apply, destroy<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> <code>init</code> is setting up your toolbox. <code>plan</code> is a dry run — a waiter reading back your order before it goes to the kitchen ("just to confirm: 2 EC2 instances, 1 S3 bucket — nothing else changes"). <code>apply</code> is sending that order to the kitchen for real. <code>destroy</code> is closing the tab and clearing the table.</div>
        <pre><span class="c"># the typical day-to-day flow</span>
terraform init      <span class="c"># downloads providers + sets up backend</span>
terraform plan      <span class="c"># shows what WOULD change — nothing is touched yet</span>
terraform apply     <span class="c"># actually creates/updates/destroys to match your code</span>
terraform destroy   <span class="c"># tears down everything Terraform manages in this state</span></pre>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>init:</strong> downloads the providers (AWS, etc.) and modules referenced in your code, and configures the backend (where state is stored).</li>
          <li><strong>plan:</strong> compares your code against the current state file and the real infrastructure, and prints a diff — green <code>+</code> for create, red <code>-</code> for destroy, yellow <code>~</code> for update in place.</li>
          <li><strong>apply:</strong> executes that plan. By default asks for a typed "yes" confirmation — <code>-auto-approve</code> skips that (common in CI pipelines, risky run manually).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">03</span> State — what it is and why it's the single most important file<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> The state file is Terraform's memory. Without it, Terraform is an amnesiac standing in front of your AWS account asking "wait, did I create this bucket, or did someone else?" The state file is what lets it say "yes, I created exactly this, here's its real ID, and here's what I'll do if you change the code."</div>
        <ul>
          <li><code>terraform.tfstate</code> maps every resource block in your code to the real-world object it created (e.g. this <code>aws_instance.web</code> block = actual EC2 instance <code>i-0abc123</code>).</li>
          <li>Local state (a file on your laptop) works for solo experiments but is dangerous for teams — two people running <code>apply</code> from different state files leads to drift and conflicts.</li>
          <li><strong>Remote state</strong> (S3 + DynamoDB lock table is the classic AWS pattern) is the real-world standard — shared, locked during operations, and versioned for recovery.</li>
        </ul>
        <pre><span class="c"># remote backend — every engineer on the team reads/writes the same state</span>
terraform {
  backend "s3" {
    bucket         = "mycompany-tfstate"
    key            = "ehs-project/prod/terraform.tfstate"
    region         = "ap-south-1"
    dynamodb_table = "tf-state-lock"
    encrypt        = true
  }
}</pre>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

