  <section class="section" id="t-resources">
    <div class="section-tag">🟪 terraform · 02</div>
    <h2>Resources, Variables &amp; State Management</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">The HCL building blocks you'll write in nearly every <code>.tf</code> file.</p>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">01</span> Resources, Data Sources &amp; Providers<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> A <strong>resource</strong> block is "build me this" — Terraform creates and owns it. A <strong>data source</strong> is "look up this thing that already exists" — Terraform just reads it, never creates or destroys it. A <strong>provider</strong> is the translator that knows how to talk to AWS/Azure/GCP's actual API.</div>
        <pre><span class="c">// provider — which cloud, which credentials/region</span>
provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-south-1"
}

<span class="c">// resource — Terraform creates and manages this</span>
resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  ami           = "ami-0c55b159cbfafe1f0"
  instance_type = "t3.micro"
  tags = { Name = "ehs-web-server" }
}

<span class="c">// data source — just reads an existing VPC, doesn't create one</span>
data "aws_vpc" "main" {
  filter {
    name   = "tag:Name"
    values = ["prod-vpc"]
  }
}</pre>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">02</span> Variables, Outputs &amp; locals<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> <code>variable</code> blocks are blank fields on a form — filled in differently per environment. <code>output</code> blocks are the receipt printed after checkout — values you want to see or hand to another part of the system. <code>locals</code> are scratch-pad notes — computed once, reused everywhere in that same file, so you're not repeating the same expression five times.</div>
        <pre><span class="c">variable "environment" {
  type    = string
  default = "dev"
}</span>

resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  instance_type = var.environment == "prod" ? "t3.large" : "t3.micro"
}

<span class="c">locals {
  name_prefix = "ehs-${var.environment}"
}</span>

resource "aws_s3_bucket" "logs" {
  bucket = "${local.name_prefix}-logs"
}

<span class="c">output "instance_ip" {
  value = aws_instance.web.public_ip
}</span></pre>
        <ul>
          <li><code>terraform.tfvars</code> — the file where you actually set variable values per environment (<code>dev.tfvars</code>, <code>prod.tfvars</code>).</li>
          <li>Variables can also come from <code>-var</code> flags, environment variables (<code>TF_VAR_environment</code>), or <code>tfvars</code> files — Terraform has a defined precedence order if multiple sources set the same variable.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">03</span> State commands — import, move, taint<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> Sometimes reality and the state file disagree — someone created a resource by hand, or you renamed something in code without telling Terraform. These commands let you correct the state file's "memory" without actually touching real infrastructure.</div>
        <pre><span class="c"># bring an existing, manually-created resource under Terraform's management</span>
terraform import aws_instance.web i-0abc123def456

<span class="c"># renamed a resource in code? tell state to follow, instead of destroy+recreate</span>
terraform state mv aws_instance.web aws_instance.web_server

<span class="c"># force a resource to be destroyed & recreated on next apply</span>
terraform taint aws_instance.web

<span class="c"># see everything Terraform currently thinks it owns</span>
terraform state list
terraform state show aws_instance.web</pre>
        <div class="gotcha-box">
          <span class="box-label">common mistake</span>
          Manually deleting a resource in the AWS console without telling Terraform. The state file still thinks it exists — next <code>plan</code> either errors out or, worse, tries to "fix" things in unexpected ways. Always run <code>terraform refresh</code> (or modern <code>plan</code>, which refreshes by default) after any out-of-band change, or better — never make out-of-band changes at all.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

