  <section class="section" id="t-modules">
    <div class="section-tag">🟪 terraform · 03</div>
    <h2>Modules &amp; Reusability</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Stop copy-pasting the same VPC/EC2 block into every project.</p>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">01</span> Modules — Terraform's reusable building blocks<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> A module is a function in a programming language — you define it once with inputs and outputs, then "call" it from anywhere with different arguments. Instead of writing the same 80-line VPC setup for every project, you write it once as a module and pass in different CIDR ranges per environment.</div>
        <pre><span class="c">// modules/ec2-app/main.tf — the reusable module</span>
variable "instance_type" {}
variable "name" {}

resource "aws_instance" "this" {
  ami           = "ami-0c55b159cbfafe1f0"
  instance_type = var.instance_type
  tags          = { Name = var.name }
}

output "public_ip" {
  value = aws_instance.this.public_ip
}</pre>
        <pre><span class="c">// root main.tf — calling the module twice, with different inputs</span>
module "ehs_app" {
  source        = "./modules/ec2-app"
  name          = "ehs-app-server"
  instance_type = "t3.medium"
}

module "monitoring" {
  source        = "./modules/ec2-app"
  name          = "monitoring-server"
  instance_type = "t3.small"
}</pre>
        <ul>
          <li><code>source</code> can point to a local path, a Git repo, or the public Terraform Registry — same syntax either way.</li>
          <li>Modules can call other modules (nesting) — common in larger setups: a root module calling a <code>networking</code> module and an <code>app</code> module, where the app module needs the VPC ID the networking module output.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">02</span> Workspaces vs separate state files for environments<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> Workspaces are like having multiple save slots in the same game file — same code, different state per slot (dev/staging/prod). It works, but most real teams find it gets confusing fast and prefer entirely separate state files (or separate Terragrunt folders) per environment for clearer isolation.</div>
        <pre><span class="c">terraform workspace new staging
terraform workspace select staging
terraform workspace list</span></pre>
        <div class="gotcha-box">
          <span class="box-label">common mistake</span>
          Using workspaces for environments that should genuinely be isolated (like dev vs prod), then accidentally running <code>apply</code> against prod because you forgot which workspace was selected. This is one of the core reasons teams move to Terragrunt's folder-per-environment pattern instead.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

