  <section class="section" id="t-commands">
    <div class="section-tag">🟪 terraform · 04</div>
    <h2>Command Cheat Sheet</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">The commands you'll type without thinking, every single day.</p>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">01</span> Everyday commands<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <table>
          <tr><th>Command</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terraform fmt</code></td><td>Auto-formats <code>.tf</code> files to canonical style — run before every commit.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terraform validate</code></td><td>Checks syntax/internal consistency without touching any infrastructure.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terraform plan -out=plan.tfplan</code></td><td>Saves the plan to a file so the exact reviewed plan is what gets applied.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terraform apply plan.tfplan</code></td><td>Applies a previously saved plan — no surprises between review and apply.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terraform plan -destroy</code></td><td>Preview what destroy would remove, without doing it.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terraform graph</code></td><td>Outputs a dependency graph (pipe into Graphviz to visualize).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terraform output</code></td><td>Print all output values from the current state.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terraform console</code></td><td>Interactive REPL to test expressions against your current state.</td></tr>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">02</span> Targeted &amp; surgical operations<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <pre><span class="c"># only plan/apply a specific resource — use sparingly, can mask dependency issues</span>
terraform apply -target=aws_instance.web

<span class="c"># pass variables inline without a .tfvars file</span>
terraform apply -var="environment=staging" -var="instance_count=3"

<span class="c"># use a specific tfvars file</span>
terraform apply -var-file="prod.tfvars"

<span class="c"># skip the interactive yes/no prompt — use carefully, mainly for CI</span>
terraform apply -auto-approve</pre>
        <div class="gotcha-box">
          <span class="box-label">common mistake</span>
          Overusing <code>-target</code> as a habit. It applies just that resource, ignoring the rest of the plan — but dependent resources elsewhere may now be out of sync with what the full plan would have produced, and the next regular <code>apply</code> can surprise you with unexpected changes.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

