  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section class="section" id="t-scenarios">
    <div class="section-tag">🟪 terraform · 05 · ⚠ daily ops</div>
    <h2>Real Office Issues — Terraform</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">The exact problems that show up in Slack on a normal Tuesday, with how to find and fix them.</p>

    <details class="item issue-item">
      <summary><span class="issue-badge">issue</span> "Error acquiring the state lock" — apply hangs or fails<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <h4>Why it happens</h4>
        <p>Someone else's <code>plan</code>/<code>apply</code> is still running (holding the DynamoDB lock), or a previous run crashed/was killed without releasing the lock cleanly.</p>
        <h4>How to investigate</h4>
        <pre><span class="c"># check who's holding the lock and since when (info shown in the error message)</span>
<span class="c"># if you're CERTAIN no one else is actually running terraform right now:</span>
terraform force-unlock &lt;LOCK_ID&gt;</pre>
        <h4>Common root causes</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>A teammate is mid-<code>apply</code> in another terminal/CI job — just wait.</li>
          <li>A CI pipeline got killed (timeout, manual cancel) mid-run and never released the lock.</li>
          <li><strong>Never</strong> force-unlock without confirming nobody else is actually running an operation — doing so while a real apply is in progress can corrupt state.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item issue-item">
      <summary><span class="issue-badge">issue</span> "Resource already exists" on apply, for something you never created<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <h4>Why it happens</h4>
        <p>The real resource exists in AWS (created manually, or by a previous Terraform run with a different state file), but it isn't tracked in your current state — so Terraform tries to create it fresh and AWS rejects the duplicate name/ID.</p>
        <h4>How to fix</h4>
        <pre><span class="c"># bring the existing resource under management instead of recreating it</span>
terraform import aws_s3_bucket.logs my-actual-bucket-name</pre>
        <div class="scenario-box">
          <span class="box-label">real office scenario</span>
          This happens constantly when someone clicks "create" in the AWS console to fix something urgently during an incident, then forgets to add it to Terraform afterward. The next person's <code>apply</code> breaks mysteriously — always <code>import</code> it properly rather than deleting the console-created resource and re-applying, if it's already serving production traffic.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item issue-item">
      <summary><span class="issue-badge">issue</span> <code>terraform plan</code> shows changes you didn't make — "drift"<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <h4>Why it happens</h4>
        <p>Someone (or some automated process, like an autoscaling action or a security tool) modified the real infrastructure outside of Terraform — the state file no longer matches reality.</p>
        <h4>How to investigate</h4>
        <pre><span class="c"># refresh state and see exactly what's different from what code expects</span>
terraform plan
<span class="c"># if it shows changes you don't want applied, investigate WHO changed it</span>
<span class="c"># in AWS, check CloudTrail for the resource ID around that time</span></pre>
        <h4>Common root causes</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Manual console "quick fixes" during an incident that never got reflected back into code.</li>
          <li>Auto-scaling, AWS Config remediation rules, or a security tool changing a setting automatically (e.g. tightening a security group).</li>
          <li>Another, separate Terraform state file accidentally managing overlapping resources.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item issue-item">
      <summary><span class="issue-badge">issue</span> State file is corrupted, lost, or out of sync after a CI failure<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <h4>Why it happens</h4>
        <p>A CI job died mid-apply (network blip, runner OOM, timeout) right as Terraform was writing the updated state — leaving a partial or inconsistent state file.</p>
        <h4>How to fix</h4>
        <pre><span class="c"># S3 backend with versioning enabled (you should always have this) —</span>
<span class="c"># restore the previous good version of the state object from S3 versioning</span>
aws s3api list-object-versions --bucket mycompany-tfstate --prefix ehs-project/prod/terraform.tfstate

<span class="c"># then re-run plan to confirm reality vs restored state matches expectations</span>
terraform plan</pre>
        <div class="gotcha-box">
          <span class="box-label">common mistake</span>
          Not enabling versioning on the S3 bucket used as the backend. Without it, a corrupted/overwritten state file has no recovery path short of painstakingly re-importing every resource by hand.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item issue-item">
      <summary><span class="issue-badge">issue</span> Apply wants to destroy and recreate a resource you only changed slightly<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <h4>Why it happens</h4>
        <p>Some attributes are "ForceNew" in the provider's schema — changing them isn't possible in-place on the real cloud API, so Terraform's only option is destroy + recreate (shown as <code>-/+</code> in the plan).</p>
        <h4>How to investigate</h4>
        <pre><span class="c"># the plan output explicitly tells you which attribute forces replacement</span>
<span class="c"># look for: "# forces replacement" next to the changed line</span>
terraform plan</pre>
        <h4>Common examples</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Changing an EC2 instance's <code>availability_zone</code> — can't move a running instance between AZs in-place.</li>
          <li>Changing an RDS instance's <code>identifier</code> — this is genuinely a different resource as far as AWS is concerned.</li>
          <li>For stateful resources like databases, always check if there's a safer in-place alternative (e.g. <code>aws_db_instance</code> has many attributes that ARE updatable — only some force replacement).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

