  <section class="section" id="t-interview">
    <div class="section-tag">🟪 terraform · 06 · ❓ interview prep</div>
    <h2>Interview Q&amp;A — Terraform</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Questions that come up again and again, answered the way you'd actually say them out loud.</p>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> What's the difference between Terraform state and the actual infrastructure?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> The state file is Terraform's record of what it created and the real-world IDs/attributes of those resources. The actual infrastructure is what genuinely exists in AWS/Azure/GCP right now. Normally these match, but they can drift apart if someone changes infrastructure outside of Terraform (console click, another tool) — that's why <code>terraform plan</code> always refreshes and compares both before showing a diff.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> Why use remote state instead of a local state file?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> Local state lives on one person's machine — it can't be safely shared, isn't locked during concurrent operations, and is one accidental <code>rm</code> away from disaster. Remote state (commonly S3 + DynamoDB for locking on AWS) gives the whole team a single source of truth, prevents two people applying simultaneously and corrupting state, and supports versioning for recovery.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> Explain the difference between a resource and a data source.<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> A <code>resource</code> block is something Terraform creates, updates, and can destroy — it owns the lifecycle. A <code>data</code> block only reads information about something that already exists (created manually, by another team, or by another Terraform state) — Terraform never modifies or destroys it, just references its attributes.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> What does <code>terraform plan</code> actually do under the hood?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> It refreshes the state by querying the real infrastructure's current attributes via the provider's API, compares that against both the existing state file and your desired configuration in code, and computes a diff — additions, in-place updates, or destroy-and-recreate — without actually executing any of it.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> How would you safely roll out a change to a critical production resource?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> Run <code>plan</code> and carefully review the diff — especially watching for any unexpected <code>-/+</code> (destroy and recreate) on stateful resources. Save the plan to a file (<code>-out</code>) so what gets reviewed is exactly what gets applied, get a second pair of eyes on it in a PR, and apply that saved plan file rather than re-running <code>apply</code> fresh (which could pick up a different diff if anything changed in between).</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> What happens if two people run <code>terraform apply</code> at the same time?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> With remote state locking configured (e.g. DynamoDB lock table alongside an S3 backend), the second person's apply is blocked with a "state lock" error until the first finishes. Without locking — like local state, or a misconfigured backend — both could write to the state file simultaneously, corrupting it. This is the core reason locking is non-negotiable for any team setup.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> When would you use <code>-target</code>, and why is it risky?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> <code>-target</code> limits an apply/plan to one specific resource — useful for an emergency fix on a single resource without touching the rest of a large plan. It's risky because Terraform's normal dependency-aware planning is bypassed for everything outside the target — other resources that depend on it (or that the full plan would have also changed) are left out of sync, and the next full apply can surprise you.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

