  <section class="section" id="g-overview">
    <div class="section-tag">🟦 terragrunt · 01</div>
    <h2>Why Terragrunt Exists</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">The thin wrapper around Terraform that solves the "same code, slightly different per environment" problem.</p>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">01</span> The problem Terragrunt solves<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> Imagine writing the exact same VPC/networking Terraform code three separate times — once for dev, once for staging, once for prod — each in its own folder with a near-identical <code>backend</code> block, just a different bucket key. Terragrunt is the person standing over your shoulder saying "stop copy-pasting that config — let's write it once and just point each environment at it."</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Plain Terraform has no built-in way to keep backend config, provider config, and common variables DRY across many environments/modules — you either copy-paste or build your own templating.</li>
          <li>Terragrunt is a thin wrapper that runs Terraform underneath, but adds: DRY backend/provider generation, dependency ordering between modules, and the ability to run a command across many modules at once.</li>
          <li>You still write standard Terraform modules — Terragrunt just orchestrates <em>how</em> they're configured and called per environment.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">02</span> terragrunt.hcl — the config file at the heart of it<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> If a Terraform module is a recipe, <code>terragrunt.hcl</code> is the index card taped above one specific stove saying "use the lasagna recipe, but with these exact ingredient amounts, and save the leftovers in container labeled 'prod'."</div>
        <pre><span class="c">// live/prod/ehs-app/terragrunt.hcl</span>
include "root" {
  path = find_in_parent_folders()
}

terraform {
  source = "../../../modules//ec2-app"
}

inputs = {
  environment   = "prod"
  instance_type = "t3.large"
}</pre>
        <ul>
          <li><code>include</code> pulls in shared config (like the backend block) from a parent <code>terragrunt.hcl</code> — no need to repeat it per environment.</li>
          <li><code>terraform { source = ... }</code> points to the actual Terraform module being used — same module, different inputs per environment folder.</li>
          <li><code>inputs</code> is just a map that gets passed straight through as Terraform variables — no separate <code>.tfvars</code> juggling needed.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!-- TERRAGRUNT SECTION 2 -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section class="section" id="g-structure">
    <div class="section-tag">🟦 terragrunt · 02</div>
    <h2>DRY Structure &amp; Dependencies</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">The folder layout real teams use, and how modules learn about each other's outputs.</p>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">01</span> The typical live/ + modules/ folder layout<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> <code>modules/</code> is the cookbook (reusable recipes). <code>live/</code> is the actual kitchen schedule — which recipe gets cooked, for which environment, with which ingredient amounts, today.</div>
        <pre><span class="c">infra/
├── terragrunt.hcl              # ROOT config: shared backend, provider generation
├── modules/
│   ├── vpc/
│   └── ec2-app/
└── live/
    ├── dev/
    │   ├── vpc/terragrunt.hcl
    │   └── ehs-app/terragrunt.hcl
    ├── staging/
    │   ├── vpc/terragrunt.hcl
    │   └── ehs-app/terragrunt.hcl
    └── prod/
        ├── vpc/terragrunt.hcl
        └── ehs-app/terragrunt.hcl</span></pre>
        <ul>
          <li>The root <code>terragrunt.hcl</code> defines the S3 backend pattern <em>once</em>, usually templated with the relative path so each environment automatically gets its own state file key.</li>
          <li>Every leaf folder (<code>live/prod/ehs-app/</code>) has a tiny <code>terragrunt.hcl</code> that just says "use this module, with these inputs" — all the repetitive boilerplate lives in the root only.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">02</span> Dependencies between modules — passing outputs automatically<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <div class="simple-box"><strong>Simple way to think about it:</strong> Your EC2 app module needs the VPC ID that the networking module created. Instead of manually copying that ID into a variable every time it changes, <code>dependency</code> blocks let one module automatically "ask" another module's already-applied state for its output values.</div>
        <pre><span class="c">// live/prod/ehs-app/terragrunt.hcl</span>
dependency "vpc" {
  config_path = "../vpc"
}

inputs = {
  vpc_id = dependency.vpc.outputs.vpc_id
}</pre>
        <ul>
          <li>Terragrunt automatically figures out it needs to apply the <code>vpc</code> module before <code>ehs-app</code> when you run <code>run-all apply</code> — dependency ordering is handled for you.</li>
          <li><code>mock_outputs</code> can be set so <code>plan</code> works even before the dependency has been applied yet (useful in fresh environments or CI dry-runs).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

