  <section class="section" id="g-commands">
    <div class="section-tag">🟦 terragrunt · 03</div>
    <h2>Command Cheat Sheet</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Mostly the same as Terraform, with a few orchestration superpowers added.</p>

    <details class="item">
      <summary><span class="num">01</span> Standard + run-all commands<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <table>
          <tr><th>Command</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terragrunt plan</code></td><td>Same as Terraform's plan, but for the current folder's module + its resolved inputs.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terragrunt apply</code></td><td>Applies just the current folder's module.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terragrunt run-all plan</code></td><td>Plans every module in and below the current folder, in dependency order.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terragrunt run-all apply</code></td><td>Applies every module in and below the current folder, respecting dependency order.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terragrunt destroy</code></td><td>Destroys just the current folder's module.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terragrunt run-all destroy</code></td><td>Destroys an entire environment's worth of modules — reverse dependency order. Use with extreme care.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>terragrunt output</code></td><td>Print outputs of the current module.</td></tr>
        </table>
        <div class="gotcha-box">
          <span class="box-label">common mistake</span>
          Running <code>run-all apply</code> from too high up the folder tree (e.g. the very top of <code>live/</code>) without realizing it'll touch <em>every environment</em> at once, including prod. Always <code>cd</code> into the specific environment folder you mean to operate on, and double check with a plan first.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

