  <!-- TERRAGRUNT SECTION 5 -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section class="section" id="g-interview">
    <div class="section-tag">🟦 terragrunt · 05 · ❓ interview prep</div>
    <h2>Interview Q&amp;A — Terragrunt</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">The questions that confirm you've actually used it on a real multi-environment setup.</p>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> What problem does Terragrunt solve that plain Terraform doesn't?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> Plain Terraform has no native way to keep backend configuration, provider blocks, and common variables DRY across many environments and modules — you end up copy-pasting near-identical boilerplate into every folder. Terragrunt is a thin wrapper that generates that shared config once, manages dependency ordering between modules, and can run commands across many modules at once (<code>run-all</code>) — while the underlying infrastructure is still defined in standard Terraform modules.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> How does Terragrunt handle dependencies between modules, like a VPC and the EC2 instances inside it?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> Through <code>dependency</code> blocks — a module's <code>terragrunt.hcl</code> can reference another module's already-applied outputs (e.g. <code>dependency.vpc.outputs.vpc_id</code>). When you run <code>run-all apply</code>, Terragrunt builds a dependency graph from these blocks and applies modules in the correct order automatically, rather than you manually sequencing <code>apply</code> commands.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> What's the risk of running <code>terragrunt run-all apply</code> carelessly?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> It applies every module found in and below your current directory. If run from too high up the folder tree — say, the root of <code>live/</code> instead of inside a specific environment folder — it can apply changes across dev, staging, AND prod in one command. Always run it from the narrowest relevant folder, and run <code>run-all plan</code> first to review exactly what's in scope.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> Terraform workspaces vs Terragrunt's folder-per-environment — which would you choose and why?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> Workspaces keep one codebase with multiple named state "slots," which is convenient but easy to misuse — applying against the wrong workspace because you forgot to switch is a real, common incident. Terragrunt's folder-per-environment approach makes the target environment explicit in the path you're standing in, removes ambiguity, and pairs naturally with per-environment input differences — most teams managing meaningfully different prod/staging/dev configurations prefer it for that clarity.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="item qa-item">
      <summary><span class="q-badge">Q</span> What are <code>mock_outputs</code> for, and when would you use them?<span class="arrow">▾</span></summary>
      <div class="item-body">
        <p><span class="answer-label">A:</span> They let a <code>dependency</code> block return placeholder values when the real dependency hasn't been applied yet — so you can still run <code>plan</code> (or even some CI validation) across an entire fresh environment before every module has real state to read outputs from. Without them, <code>plan</code> on a dependent module would simply fail until its dependencies are applied first.</p>
        </div>
    </details>
